{
  "slug": "gladiator-ii-is-here-are-we-not-entertained",
  "title": "‘Gladiator II’ Is Here. Are We Not Entertained?",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Chris Ryan",
    "Mallory Rubin"
  ],
  "published": "2024-11-22",
  "runtimeMin": 114,
  "format": "Sean, Chris, and Mallory, a trio that hasn't potted together since the Inglourious Basterds Rewatchables, dig into Ridley Scott's long-delayed sequel, a movie they found hugely entertaining and a huge disappointment at the same time. Denzel Washington runs off with it; Paul Mescal fights CGI baboons. Then a top-five legacy sequels draft, one list each.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Gladiator II’",
      "note": "spoilers flagged 50 minutes in",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Gladiator II",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Structurally a near one-to-one redo of the first film with the politics flipped, which keeps inviting a comparison it can't win. Denzel Washington's Macrinus, a freed slave and arms dealer improvising his way to power, is the best thing in it; Mescal's Lucius, revealed as Maximus's son, gets buried under CGI baboons, a rhino, and a shark battle. Everyone loved the intimate hand-to-hand fights and the twin-emperor debauchery (Fred Hechinger, Joseph Quinn); everyone found the movie messy. Empty-calorie Ridley: a fun night out, not a serious film."
        },
        {
          "title": "Gladiator",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "The measuring stick, and by their read arguably the last truly practical blockbuster, with little CGI beyond the wide shots of Rome. The sequel's Skywalker-style retcon (Lucius as Maximus's son) sent Mallory back through her memory of a film she'd rewatched three days earlier."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Sean's Top Five Legacy Sequels",
      "note": "director revisits the work much later",
      "ranked": true,
      "subject": "legacy sequels",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Mad Max: Fury Road",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "No. 1 — one of the greatest movies of the century; Max is almost incidental to the world and the experience."
        },
        {
          "title": "Top Gun: Maverick",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "No. 2 — the degree of difficulty is higher than Fury Road's, and he can't name one person who didn't like it. Val Kilmer's scene got him."
        },
        {
          "title": "Doctor Sleep",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "No. 3 — the director's cut. Disliked it the first time; the longer version made it one of his favorites of the last 10 years. Flanagan as the coming Stephen King 'Kevin Feige.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Texas Chainsaw Massacre 2",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "No. 4 — same filmmaker, 12 to 13 years later, swapping horror for slapstick, with a ludicrous Dennis Hopper as the hero."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Color of Money",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "No. 5 — also Chris's No. 1. Scorsese and Richard Price find Paul Newman's Eddie Felson in his twilight, mentoring a protégé; to Chris, better than The Hustler."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Mallory's Top Five Legacy Sequels",
      "note": "director revisits the work much later",
      "ranked": true,
      "subject": "legacy sequels",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Before Midnight",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "No. 1 — the guts Gladiator II lacked: what if these people actually wound up together, and it was hard? A raw, very French reckoning; the Before trilogy is one of her three favorite trilogies."
        },
        {
          "title": "Logan",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "No. 2 — also Chris's No. 2. One of her favorite comic-book movies; Daphne Keen, Hugh Jackman, and Patrick Stewart bridging old and new. 'Desecrated by Deadpool & Wolverine.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Mad Max: Fury Road",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "No. 3 — first saw it at the Vista on release, 'electrifying,' one of her favorite theater memories."
        },
        {
          "title": "Top Gun: Maverick",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "No. 4 — inseparable from the COVID-era moment of gathering to share something, but it holds up absent that context."
        },
        {
          "title": "Star Wars: The Force Awakens",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "No. 5 — maps closely onto A New Hope (Starkiller Base, Jakku, BB-8) but far more successful at launching a trilogy than The Phantom Menace. She'd argue The Last Jedi is the better film."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Chris's Top Five Legacy Sequels",
      "note": "director revisits the work much later",
      "ranked": true,
      "subject": "legacy sequels",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Color of Money",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "No. 1 — the most magical revisiting of a text he can think of, and better than the original."
        },
        {
          "title": "Logan",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "No. 2 — one of his three favorite comic-book movies, alongside The Dark Knight and Into the Spider-Verse."
        },
        {
          "title": "Before Midnight",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "No. 3 — one of the most beautiful movies ever made; a portrait of youth revisited two decades on."
        },
        {
          "title": "T2 Trainspotting",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "No. 4 — came and went despite the original's cultural impact; middle-aged men reckoning with their masculinity in Danny Boyle's throw-everything-at-the-wall style. Underrated."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Exorcist III",
          "year": 1990,
          "note": "No. 5 (tie) — William Peter Blatty's return, 13 years after the second film; a straight-up great horror movie that's also provocative about the first film's ideas."
        },
        {
          "title": "2010: The Year We Make Contact",
          "year": 1984,
          "note": "No. 5 (tie) — Peter Hyams following Kubrick, with Roy Scheider and Helen Mirren; sacrilegious for trying to answer 2001's questions, and Chris likes it anyway."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
